description: Between 1973 and 1979 World Distributors released seven Wombles Annuals to tie in with the Wombles children's TV show. The series was so successful that they also released several stand alone volumes in the annual format, but not using the title annual, including The Wombles Bumper Book, The Wombles Make-Good-Use-Of-Rubbish Book, The World of the Wombles and The Wombles Book - Stories for Young Children. PBS Ltd also released The Wombles Colour Story Book in 1976, reprinting material from Wombles Annual 1974. Following the Wombles Annual 1980 (dated 1980 but released 1979) there was a gap of several years before World Distributors (under their new name, World International Publishing Ltd) released any further Wombles Annuals, with the next two being Wombles Annual 1990 (released 1989, and reprinting material from the 1979 and 1980 Annuals) and Wombles Annual 1999 (released 1998, to coincide with a new Wombles TV series).
name: Wombles Annual

description: In 1973 Hamburg-based publisher Williams Verlag became the German license holder for reprinting Marvel comics, previously only sporadically reprinted there. In January 1974 Verlag launched a line of Marvel titles, which included horror title Das Monster von Frankenstein, reprinting the US Marvel series The Monster of Frankenstein translated into German by Hartmut Huff, with back-up features usually provided by Atlas-era horror short stories.Marvel US' series, retitled in later issues as The Frankenstein Monster, had ended abruptly mid-story with #18; unusually, Verlag opted to continue the story when they reached this point in their reprint run, and Das Monster von Frankenstein #26 thus contained a brand new story written by Huff which carried on from where the US strip ended. From #27 on, the series began reprinting colourised versions of the Monster's stories from Monsters Unleashed. The series cancelled with issue #33.
name: Das Monster von Frankenstein

description: Disney Time was a licensed weekly Disney comic published in the U.K. by IPC. The first issue was cover dated 29th January 1977. It was cancelled after 21 issues on 18th June 1977 and merged with Mickey Mouse in Disneyland, which was renamed Mickey Mouse and Disney Time. There were two specials, a "Fun Time Special" and Holiday Special, and, despite the weekly title having such a brief life, 8 Disney Time Annuals.
name: Disney Time

description: Though Marvel UK had begun publishing Marvel's weekly titles in the UK from the early 1970s, rather than licensing out the rights to do reprints to other companies, for several years production of Marvel annuals in the UK were still licensed out, increasingly becoming a co-production between Marvel UK and Grandreams, so that by the late 1970s it was common to see an annual identify itself as "Marvel/Grandreams". However, earlier in the 1970s the rights resided with World Distributors, who were responsible for starting a short-lived line of Avengers Annuals.
name: Avengers Annual

description: In 1982 Marvel UK released two Blake's 7 seasonal specials to tie in with their Blake's 7 magazine. With the monthly title's cancellation after the TV show went off air, that seemed to be it for the specials too, but towards the end of 1994 Marvel UK began publishing the Blake's 7 Poster Magazine, and to tie-in with that, two new specials were released: Winter 1995 (actually released November 1994) and Summer 1995. With the Poster Magazine's poor sales and resultant swift cancellation, no further specials were published.
name: Blake's 7 Special

description: Most of the UK Star Trek Annuals, starting from the first in 1969, were published by World Distributors and reprinted Gold Key's Star Trek series. However, with the advent of the Motion Picture, the 1981 Annual was published by Grandreams and reprinted Marvel's adaptation of the movie, while the 1983 Annual, released to tie in with Wrath of Khan, was published by Stafford Pemberton (though, despite the movie being namechecked on the cover, the actual stories within were again Gold Key reprints). The final Star Trek Annual, released in 1985, saw the license back with World Distributors.
name: Star Trek Annual

description: In 1952 Gerald G. Swan started a new line, Picture Epics, gathering together stories previously spread across several of their titles. Four issues were published between October and November 1952 before the line concluded.
